[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] As an explanatory analogy, Apache TinkerPop and Gremlin are to graph databases what the JDBC and SQL are to relational databases.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Likewise, the Gremlin traversal machine is to graph computing as what the Java virtual machine is to general purpose computing.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Gremlin is an Apache2-licensed graph traversal language that can be used by graph system vendors.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] There are typically two types of graph system vendors: OLTP graph databases and OLAP graph processors.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The table below outlines those graph vendors that support Gremlin.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The following examples of Gremlin queries and responses in a Gremlin-Groovy environment are relative to a graph representation of the MovieLens dataset.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The dataset includes users who rate movies.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Users each have one occupation, and each movie has one or more categories associated with it.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The MovieLens graph schema is detailed below.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Gremlin supports declarative graph pattern matching similar to SPARQL.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] For instance, the following query below uses Gremlin's *match()*-step.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Gremlin is a virtual machine composed of an instruction set as well as an execution engine.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] An analogy is drawn between Gremlin and Java.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The following traversal is a Gremlin traversal in the Gremlin-Java8 dialect.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The Gremlin language (i.e. the fluent-style of expressing a graph traversal) can be represented in any host language that supports function composition and function nesting.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Due to this simple requirement, there exists various Gremlin dialects including Gremlin-Groovy, Gremlin-Scala, Gremlin-Clojure, etc.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The above Gremlin-Java8 traversal is ultimately compiled down to a step sequence called a *traversal*.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] A string representation of the traversal above provided below.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The *steps* are the primitives of the Gremlin graph traversal machine.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] They are the parameterized instructions that the machine ultimately executes.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The Gremlin instruction set is approximately 30 steps.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] These steps are sufficient to provide general purpose computing and what is typically required to express the common motifs of any graph traversal query.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Given that Gremlin is a language, an instruction set, and a virtual machine, it is possible to design another traversal language that compiles to the Gremlin traversal machine (analogous to how Scala compiles to the JVM).
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] For instance, the popular SPARQL graph pattern match language can be compiled to execute on the Gremlin machine.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] In Gremlin-Java8, the SPARQL query above would be represented as below and compile to the identical Gremlin step sequence (i.e. traversal).
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] The Gremlin graph traversal machine can execute on a single machine or across a multi-machine compute cluster.
[src:janusgraph/apache-tinkerpop] Execution agnosticism allows Gremlin to run over both graph databases (OLTP) and graph processors (OLAP).
[src:janusgraph/architecture] JanusGraph itself is focused on compact graph serialization, rich graph data modeling, and efficient query execution.
[src:janusgraph/architecture] In addition, JanusGraph utilizes Hadoop for graph analytics and batch graph processing.
[src:janusgraph/architecture] JanusGraph implements robust, modular interfaces for data persistence, data indexing, and client access.
[src:janusgraph/architecture] JanusGraph’s modular architecture allows it to interoperate with a wide range of storage, index, and client technologies; it also eases the process of extending JanusGraph to support new ones.
[src:janusgraph/architecture] Between JanusGraph and the disks sits one or more storage and indexing adapters.
[src:janusgraph/architecture] JanusGraph comes standard with the following adapters, but JanusGraph’s modular architecture supports third-party adapters.
[src:janusgraph/blob-readme-md] JanusGraph is a highly scalable graph database optimized for storing and querying large graphs with billions of vertices and edges distributed across a multi-machine cluster.
[src:janusgraph/blob-readme-md] JanusGraph is a transactional database that can support thousands of concurrent users, complex traversals, and analytic graph queries.
[src:janusgraph/blob-readme-md] The project homepage contains more information on JanusGraph and provides links to documentation, getting-started guides and release downloads.
[src:janusgraph/blob-readme-md] JanusGraph has a web-based graph visualizer located in janusgraph-visualizer repository.
[src:janusgraph/blob-readme-md] Please see `CONTRIBUTING.md` for more information, including CLAs and best practices for working with GitHub.
[src:janusgraph/blob-readme-md] The following users have deployed JanusGraph in production.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:janusgraph/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] JanusGraph is designed to support the processing of graphs so large that they require storage and computational capacities beyond what a single machine can provide.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] Scaling graph data processing for real time traversals and analytical queries is JanusGraph’s foundational benefit.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] This section will discuss the various specific benefits of JanusGraph and its underlying, supported persistence solutions.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] When using a database, the CAP theorem should be thoroughly considered (C=Consistency, A=Availability, P=Partition tolerance).
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] JanusGraph is distributed with 3 supporting backends: Apache Cassandra, Apache HBase, and Oracle Berkeley DB Java Edition.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] Note that BerkeleyDB JE is a non-distributed database and is typically only used with JanusGraph for testing and exploration purposes.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] HBase gives preference to consistency at the expense of yield, i.e. the probability of completing a request.
[src:janusgraph/docs-janusgraph-org] Cassandra gives preference to availability at the expense of harvest, i.e. the completeness of the answer to the query (data available/complete data).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:janusgraph/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
